{"parentUuid":"d85802de-ebba-4cbb-8510-e738715ceeff","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"e57c52ef-3627-4a2e-a8e9-5764367169c6","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01GqmMqhfjw2BCZr9KkfZqze","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect. Now I have all the information I need. Let me compile the architectural friction report:\n\n## Architectural Friction Report: Cross-Agent Skills Collection\n\n### 1. SKILL.md Summaries\n\n**session-handoff**: Detects active sessions, reads transcripts, produces compaction summaries, and supports checkpoint handoff across agents.\n\n**explain**: Traces code back to original sessions via git blame and transcript lookup to explain why code exists.\n\n**search**: Searches Entire checkpoint history to find prior work by topic, repo, author, or time.\n\n**what-happened**: Traces latest changes to code blocks via git blame and deduplicates checkpoint lookups; includes fallback code behavior analysis.\n\n**Duplication flags:**\n- All four SKILL.md files follow identical response format templates: \"Entire <skillname>:\" header on first response only, no header on error/early-exit (lines 9-23 in session-handoff.md, lines 14-23 in explain.md, lines 9-18 in search.md, lines 224-237 in what-happened.md).\n- explain and what-happened both delegate to `entire explain --commit` with near-identical fallback logic (explain.md:32, what-happened.md:143-160).\n- search and session-handoff both use `entire explain --checkpoint` with identical fallback patterns: `--full` → `--raw-transcript` (session-handoff.md:99-101, search.md:46-55).\n- Three skills share identical deduplication patterns before running transcript expansion (session-handoff.md:72-75, what-happened.md:143-165, search.md:30-56).\n\n### 2. Plugin Manifest Duplication\n\n**Unified across all 6 manifests:**\n- name: \"entire\" (consistent)\n- version: \"0.3.0\" (identical across all)\n- description: \"Cross-agent skills and commands powered by Entire\" (word-for-word in claude, codex; +period in cursor/gemini)\n- author: \"Entire Inc\" (standardized)\n- keywords: overlap 100% on core terms (entire, session-handoff, handoff, skills, agent-workflows)\n\n**Agent-specific differences:**\n- Claude Code: includes marketplace.json (lines 3-4) with category \"development\" and schema reference; plugin.json lacks `interface` field\n- Codex: adds `interface.displayName`, `capabilities: [Interactive, Write]` (lines 22-30); .codex/config.toml enables `codex_hooks = true` (line 3)\n- Cursor: minimal—only `displayName`, `keywords` (line 12); no interface/capabilities\n- Gemini: standalone gemini-extension.json with minimal metadata + contextFileName: \"GEMINI.md\" (line 5)\n- OpenCode: separate entire.js plugin (auto-registers skills path via config hook, lines 16-23)\n- Agents (Codex secondary): marketplace.json with `policy.installation: AVAILABLE` and `authentication: ON_INSTALL` (lines 13-15)\n\n**Friction point**: Same metadata duplicated across 6 files with trivial dialect differences (period, displayName presence, capabilities field). Version bumps require updates in all 6 locations.\n\n### 3. OpenCode Plugin Logic\n\nThe `.opencode/plugins/entire.js` file (lines 1-24) is a **config-hook plugin** that auto-injects the skills directory into OpenCode's config on startup. It does not perform Entire-specific operations—it's a generic skill-discovery pattern that could plausibly fit any agent's manifest system if adapted to that agent's hook API (e.g., Claude Code hooks in .claude/settings.json or Codex hooks in .codex/hooks.json).\n\n**Not unique to OpenCode**: This pattern is generalizable; other agents could use similar hooks to auto-register the skills directory without manual installation.\n\n### 4. README.md Install Section Friction\n\nLines 68-162 in README.md contain 7 separate per-agent install blocks:\n- Claude Code (lines 79-85): 2-command plugin marketplace flow\n- Cursor (lines 88-98): git clone to ~/.cursor/skills/entire with auto-discovery note\n- Gemini (lines 102-110): gemini extensions CLI\n- OpenCode (lines 113-123): git clone to ~/.agents/skills/entire with auto-discovery note\n- Codex (lines 126-135): git clone to ~/.agents/skills/entire with update command\n- Copilot (lines 138-145): plugin install or git clone to ~/.copilot/skills/\n- Antigravity (lines 152-162): git clone and symlink to ~/.antigravity/skills/entire\n\n**Repetition pattern**: Cursor, OpenCode, and Codex all use identical `git clone ~/.agents/skills/` pattern with auto-discovery. Copilot and Antigravity are similar. Only Claude Code and Gemini deviate (marketplace API, gemini CLI).\n\n**Coupling**: Claude Code and Codex install instructions reference agent-specific flows (marketplace, hooks) that are not portable; others are generic git clone + auto-discovery.\n\n### 5. Agent Config & Runtime Coupling\n\n**Claude Code (.claude/settings.json, lines 2-76)**:\n- 6 hook handlers bound to Claude Code runtime hooks (SessionStart, SessionEnd, Stop, UserPromptSubmit, PreToolUse/PostToolUse with Task/TodoWrite matchers)\n- Commands invoke `entire hooks claude-code <subcommand>`\n- Skill execution is directly coupled to Claude Code's hook lifecycle\n\n**Codex (.codex/hooks.json, lines 2-39 + .codex/config.toml, line 3)**:\n- 3 hook handlers bound to Codex runtime (SessionStart, Stop, UserPromptSubmit)\n- Commands invoke `entire hooks codex <subcommand>`\n- Feature flag `codex_hooks = true` enables hook execution\n- Skill execution is directly coupled to Codex's hook lifecycle\n- Codex agent subconfig (.codex/agents/entire-search.toml, lines 1-23) defines a read-only search subagent with `entire search --json` as the sole history mechanism\n\n**OpenCode (.opencode/plugins/entire.js)**:\n- Plugin config hook only; no runtime lifecycle coupling\n\n**Cursor, Gemini, Copilot, Antigravity**:\n- No config files present; skill discovery is passive (git clone to predefined paths)\n\n**Friction point**: Claud