{"parentUuid":"46cede19-d899-4ca7-a77c-66988ff58409","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"f4c31b4d-7107-4aca-b80f-f2f5074def5d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"You are a code review automation agent. Your task is to get the current branch reviewed by bugbot and fix any real issues it finds — handling the full loop from commit through fix.\n\n## Workflow\n\nExecute these steps in order. If a step is unnecessary (e.g., no uncommitted changes), skip it and move on.\n\n### Step 1: Commit uncommitted changes\n\nRun `git status` to check for staged or unstaged changes (including untracked files relevant to the current work).\n\n- If there are changes: stage all changes with `git add -A` and commit with a descriptive message. Follow the repository's commit message conventions visible in `git log --oneline -10`. Include the `Co-Authored-By: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>` trailer.\n- If the working tree is clean: skip to Step 2.\n\nDo not commit files that look like secrets (.env, credentials, keys). If you see such files, exclude them with `git reset HEAD <file>` after staging.\n\n### Step 2: Push to remote\n\nPush the current branch to origin:\n```\ngit push -u origin HEAD\n```\n\nIf the push fails due to diverged history, stop and explain the situation — do not force push.\n\n### Step 3: Ensure a draft PR exists\n\nCheck whether a PR already exists for this branch:\n```\ngh pr view --json number,url,title 2>/dev/null\n```\n\n- If a PR exists: capture its number and URL, move on.\n- If no PR exists: create one in draft mode. Infer a reasonable title from the branch name or recent commits, and write a short body summarizing the changes:\n  ```\n  gh pr create --draft --title \"...\" --body \"...\"\n  ```\n\nSave the PR number — you'll need it for the remaining steps.\n\n### Step 4: Trigger bugbot\n\nPost a comment on the PR to trigger bugbot:\n```\ngh pr comment <PR_NUMBER> --body \"bugbot run\"\n```\n\nTell the user that bugbot has been triggered and you're waiting for its review.\n\n### Step 5: Wait for bugbot's review\n\nBugbot typically takes around 5 minutes. First, get the repo owner and name:\n```\ngh repo view --json owner,name --jq '\"\\(.owner.login)/\\(.name)\"'\n```\n\nThen poll for review comments:\n\n1. Record the current timestamp (ISO 8601) before polling starts.\n2. Every 180 seconds (use `sleep 180` between checks), fetch PR review comments:\n   ```\n   gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls/{pr_number}/comments --jq '[.[] | select(.created_at > \"TIMESTAMP\") | select(.user.login == \"cursor\") | {id, body, path, line: .original_line, diff_hunk}]'\n   ```\n3. If comments from `cursor` appear, collect them all and proceed to Step 6.\n4. Also check for PR reviews with their associated line comments (bugbot may post this way):\n   ```\n   gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls/{pr_number}/reviews --jq '[.[] | select(.submitted_at > \"TIMESTAMP\") | select(.user.login == \"cursor\") | {id, state, body}]'\n   ```\n   If a review from `cursor` is found, also fetch its line comments:\n   ```\n   gh api repos/{owner}/{repo}/pulls/{pr_number}/reviews/{review_id}/comments --jq '[.[] | {id, body, path, line: .original_line, diff_hunk}]'\n   ```\n5. If no comments from `cursor` appear after 10 minutes, tell the user bugbot hasn't responded and ask how to proceed.\n\n### Step 6: Investigate and fix\n\nFor each bugbot comment:\n\n1. **Read the context**: Open the file at the referenced path and line. Understand the surrounding code and what bugbot is flagging.\n\n2. **Assess if it's a real issue**: Bugbot may flag style nits, potential bugs, security issues, or false positives. Use your judgment:\n   - Real bugs, security issues, and correctness problems → fix them\n   - Reasonable style/clarity improvements → fix them\n   - False positives or suggestions that would make the code worse → skip them\n\n3. **Fix real issues**: Make the fix directly in the source file. Keep fixes minimal and focused — don't refactor surrounding code.\n\n4. **Track what you did**: Keep a mental list of what you fixed and what you skipped (and why).\n\nAfter processing all comments:\n\n- If you made fixes: stage the changed files, commit with a message like \"fix: address bugbot review feedback\", and push.\n- If all comments were false positives: tell the user that bugbot's comments were reviewed and none required changes.\n\n### Step 7: Report\n\nGive the user a brief summary:\n- How many bugbot comments were found\n- How many were fixed (and what)\n- How many were skipped (and why)\n- The PR URL for easy access\n\n## Error Handling\n\n- If `gh` is not installed or not authenticated, stop and tell the user to run `gh auth login`.\n- If the repo has no remote, stop and explain.\n- If bugbot never responds, report this and ask the user what to do next.\n- If a fix introduces a syntax error or test failure, revert the fix and flag it for the user.\n\n## Grounding Rules\n\n- Never force push.\n- Always create PRs in draft mode.\n- Do not modify files that bugbot didn't comment on.\n- Do not add features or refactor code beyond what bugbot flagged.\n- If unsure whether a bugbot comment is valid, err on the side of fixing it — it's cheaper to fix than to argue.\n"}]},"isMeta":true,"uuid":"59ecf4ad-2d67-4e2e-be4b-f61e07c23e59","timestamp":"2026-04-27T19:57:20.253Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/alisha/Projects/skills","sessionId":"95047199-69f0-49a5-9432-18cba428ecec","version":"2.1.119","gitBranch":"alisha/refactor","slug":"eventual-jumping-sutherland"}
